{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_indeed_ver02/data/sn92051126/0051717421A/1910110401/0595.xml":{"full_text":"THE NEW HAVEN UNION\nFOUNDED BY ALEXANDER TROUP.\nFRIDAY, NOVEMBER 4, 1910.\nELEVENTH-HOUR AWAKENING OF AN EVENING\nThis paper has never assailed the integrity or\ncharacter of Senator Blakeslee as a citizen of thi3\ncommunity or as a business man, and it has recog\nnized the conspicuous and deserving place he occu\npies in the world of business.\nBut in that other world, the world of politics, we\nhave said a few sharp things about this leading Re\npublican and we repeat for the benefit of an evening\ncontemporary, that has so suddenly and significantly\njumped to the defense of Senator Blakeslee\u2014a sort\nof an eleventh-hour jump, too, by the way\u2014that his\nstandard of politics is not the standard, or the quality,\nor the kind that appeals to The Union, or, in our\njudgment, appeals to the reason or commendation of\nfair-minded citizens generally.\nWe think his mind is warped politically, that is,\nhe cannot see anything Commendable that is urged or\nendorsed by a Democrat. His partisanship is alto\ngether too rank for progress, for that which makes\n&r the common good. Politically, in a word, he is too\nnarrow for the development of this age. He would\nnever, in our judgment, make up his mind that Demo\ncratic men or measures were for the public welfare\nuntil he had first sized up just how far those Demo\ncratic men and measures could be used for the bene\nfit of the Republican party. Well, that is a sample of\npolitical selfishness that goes against our grain.\nPersonally, he is a very nice gentleman. Politi\ncally, he should have his wings clipped and now is\nthe time to clip them before he gets into the chair of\nthe lieutenant-governor. Keep him to home, as we\nhave said before.\nnow, mere are .Republicans in this community\nwho are impressed occasionally with the idea and- act\nin accordance therewith, that all Democrats are not\nas black as some wild-eyed Republican high brow of\nan editor might paint them. Senator Blakeslee isn\u2019t\nin that generous class, never has been, and from\nexisting conditions, never will be. And as Demo\ncrats, we have no use for him. This is all political,\nnot personal. His whole record in Hartford, in the\nLegislature, has been a record that cannot commend\nitself to Democrats. And to the suggestion of our\nevening contemporary that citizens \"of this town\nshould vote for Blakeslee, the Republican, just be\ncause he is a resident of New Haven, we would reply\nthat the Democrats of New Haven should pay no at\ntention to such an appeal, It is well enough to shout\nlong and vigorously on the local pride note, but when\npolitics is involved and such politics as Senator\nBlakeslee stands for and has always stood for, The\nUnion must enter an emphatic veto. And by the way,\nnow that it comes to our mind, has any one heard or\nread that such a distinguished worker for the Repub\nlican cause as The Hartford Courant is pleading\nwith the Republicans of Hartford to support the able\nDemocrat in that city named for lieutenant-gover\nnor because he is a successful citizen and on the\nground of local pride? Not so that you could hear it.\nRepublicans in that city would laugh at such a sug\ngestion, just as the Democrats in this city grin oyer\nthe suggestion of our evening eleventh-hour contem\nporary that Democrats vote for Blakeslee for lieu\ntenant governor.\nWe say to the Democrats: Vote against Good\nwin, Blakeslee and every other Republican on the\nstate ticket by putting in a straight Democratic ticket.\nWEDNESDAY NIGHT\u2019S REPUBLICAN RALLY\nPour speakers held forth at the Re\npublican rally In the Hyperion theater\nWednesday evening to voice an appeal\nfor their ticket in this campaign. Let\nus consider the remarks of these gen\ntlemen in the order in which they ap\npeared.\nJOH1V Q. TILSON\u2019S speech.\nFIRST ACTING AS PRESIDING\nOFFICER OF THE EVENING WF\nHAVE MR. JOHN Q. TILSON\u2014TIC\nSAME TILSON WHO WAS ONE OF\nTHE FOLLOWERS OF JOE CAN\nNON IN THE FAST HOUSE OF REP\nIRESENTA'ITVES AND WHOSE REC\npRb WAS SO OPPOSED TO THE\nTlEST INTERESTS OF THE PEOPLE\nTHAT THE CONNECTICUT STATE\nFEDERATION OF LABOR IN CON\nVENTION ASSEMBLED AT I> \\N\nBURY RECENTLY CONDEMNED\nHIM, TOGETHER WITH THE OTH\nER REPUBLICAN MEMBERS OF\nTHE CONNECTICUT DELEGATION\nIN CONGRESS. AS UNWORTHY OF\nTHE SUPPORT OF GOOD CITIZENS\nAT THE POLLS.\nIn opening his remarks Congress\nman Tiison harked back, as is the\npractice of Republican orators and in\nvoked the shades of Abraham Lincoln.\nMr. Tiison forgets that Lincoln was\nreally a follower of Thomas Jefferson,\nthe founder of the Democratic party.\nHe forgets that were Lincoln alive to\nday lie would denounce the Republi\ncan party for the way In which it has\nPlaced capital above labor in its con\nsideration of national problems. Lin\ncoln recognized this tendency even in\nhis own day and a warning against it\ncan be found in his message to Con\ngress on December 3, 1S61.\nNOT T HE PARTY OF I.TNCOLN.\nThe Republican party at the pres\nent time is a. far different organization\nthan the Republican party as Lincoln\nknew it and the development of the\ncountry since Lincoln's time has pro\ngressed not, because of, but In spite of\nRepublican legislation. Mr. Tiison is\nentirely mistaken when he says that\nthe development of this country slneo\nthe Civil war under high tariffs has\nbeen the greatest ever known. Even\nMr. Barbour contradicted Mr. Ttlson\non this score and quoted figures show\ning that our national values Increased\nto a greater extent for ten years prior\nto the Civil war than they have since.\n11115 PANIC OF 1893.\nAlthough we are now commenting\non Mr. Tilson\u2019s remarks, we might just\nas well dispose of Mr. Barbour's argu\nment right now. Mr. Barbour practi\ncally admitted that this country en\njoyed greater prosperity in the pro\nduction of national wealth under the\nlow tariffs in force from 1840 to 1800\nthan wo have ever enjoyed since; but\nhe tried to destroy the force of this\nfact, supported as it is by official fig\nures. by reading a portion of a presi\ndential message sent to Congress at the\ntime of che panic of 1S57.\nMR. HARBOUR TOOK PARTICU\nIiAR DELIGHT IN SPEAKING OF\nTIHS PANIC AND THE PANIC OF\n1893 BOTH OF WHICH OCCURRED\nIN DEMOCRATIC ADMINISTRA\nTIONS; HUT WERE DUE TO CAUSES\nOVER WHICH HIE DEMOCRATIC\nPARTY HAD NO CONTROL.\nMR. HARBOUR WITH ALL UTS\nALLEGED AND ASSUMED CANDID\nNESS TOLD HIS AUDIENCE NOTH\nING ABOUT THE PANICS OF 189\u00ab1,\nOF 1873. OF 1882, OF 1907. ALL OF\nWHICH OCCURRED UNDER RE\nPUBLICAN ADMINISTRATIONS. He\ndid not inform his audience\nthat this panic of 1893,\nwhich Republicans cling to as a\ndrowning man does to a straw, oc\ncurred while the Republican McKin\nley tariff bill was In force and before\nthe Wilson bill was enacted Into law.\nHuman ingeunity and malice combin\ned never invented a more stupend\nous slander than this one so often re\npeated that the panic of 1893 was\nproduced by the Wilson tariff bill,\nwhich as a matter of fact was not en\nacted into law until In August, 1894.\nThe facts In regard to the panic of\n1893 are substantially as follows:\nOCCURRED UNDER McKINLEY\nBILL.\nThe Republican party was restored\nto power in 1889 by the inauguration\nof Benjamin Harrison as President.\nThe Republican McKinley tariff bill\nbecame a law October 6, IS 90, and\nAFTER\nSUFFERING\nCured by Lydia E. Pink\nham\u2019sVegetable Compound\nMilwaukee, Wis. \u201cLydia E. Pink\nham\u20193 Vegetable Compound has made\nmo a well woman,\nand I would like to\ntell the whole world\nof it. I suffered\nfromfemale trouble\nand fearful painsin\nmy back. I had the\nbest doctors and\nthey all decided\nthat I had a tumor\nin addition to my\nfemale trouble, ana\nadvised an opera\ni_iz_r non. Lyaia e.\nPinkham\u2019s Vegetable Compound made\nme a well woman and I have no more\nbackache. I hope I can help others by\ntelling them what Lydia E. Pinkham\u2019s\nVegetable Compound has done for\nme.\u201d\u2014Mrs. EmmaImse, 833EirstSt.,\nMilwaukee, Wis.\nThe above is only one of the thou\nsands of grateful letters which are\nconstantly being received by the\nPinkham Medicine Company of Lynn,\nMass..which prove beyond a doubt that\nLydia E. Pinkham\u2019s Vegetable Com\npound, made from root3 and herbs,\nactually does cure these obstinate dis\neases of women after all other means\nhave failed, and that every such suf\nering worhan owes it to herself to at\nleast give Lydia E. Pinkham\u2019s Vegeta\nble Compound a trial before submit\nting to an operation, or giving up\nhope of recovery.\nMrs. Pinkham, of Lynn, Mass.,\ninvites all sick women to write\nher for advice. She lias guided\nthousands to health and her\nadvice is free.\nremained in effect until August 27,\n1894, when It was supplanted by the\nWilson bill. The first indications of\nthe so-called panic of 1893 became\nevident November 11, 1890, a little\nmore than thirty days after the Re\npublican McKinley tariff bill became\na law. From that date on the panic\nraped and became so bad that before\nhalf of the term of Harrison had ex\npired, he made arrangements to nego\ntiate a bond deal to tide over the gov\nernment and even went so far as to\nhave the bond plates struck off for this\npurpose. These are facts that Mr.\nBarbour or Mr. Tilson did not mention\nand which they cannot and will not\ndeny.\nMR. BARBOUR KNOWS BETTER.\nYet Mr. Barbour had the gall when\nheckled Wednesday night by an audi\ntor and asked to explain the cause of\nthe panic of 1893 to attribute it to a\nDemocratic- administration. OF\nCOURSE MR. BARBOUR SILENT SO\nI-ONi; IN THIS CAMPAIGN, WAS\nPROBABLY PAID WELL FOR\nBREAKING THAT SILENCE EVEN'\nAT THIS LATE DAY. We cannot how\never have any more confidence in the\nreal sincerity of his remarks than one\ncan have In the attorney hired to argue\na certain case. Certainly Mr. Barbour\nis grossly unfair in this whole 1893\npanic business and we suspect that no\nbody knows that fact better than Joe\nBarbour himself.\nREPUBLICAN PANICS.\nEven the Republican campaign text\nbook for 1904 (pages 125, 12fi and\n1271 gives over considerable space to\na statement of business disasters from\nJuly 18, 1893 until the end of the\npanic in November, 1894. which is nn\nadmission that the panic started while\nthe McKinley tariff bill was in force\nand ended within a few weeks after\nthe Wilson bill had been enacted into\nlav-. IF REPUBLICAN ORATORS\nWOULD SPEND MORE TIME EX\nPLAINING US REPUBLICAN PAN\nIIS OF ISfii), 1873. 1881 AND 1907\nTHEY WOULD HAVE LESS TI.ME\nTO LIE ABOUT THE PANIC OF\n1893.\nAll these panics occurred under\nhigh tariffs. No historian or political\neconomist of note, with the exception\nof Mr. Barbiour, has ever intimated\nthat the panic of 1857 was due to the\nlow tariffs in force at that time. It\nwas due to disturbances connected\nwith our monetary system. This is gen\nerally admitted.\nHIGH AND LOW TARIFF I'BUK\nPTJRITY.\nHere are a few more facts that Mr.\nBarbour did not bring out in this\nconnection which may be of interest\nto the reader. During the low tariff\nperiod from 1840 to 1860 our ships\ncarried 70 per cent, of the tonnage of\nthe world, while In 1871, under a high\ntariff it had fallen to 14 per cent, and\nin 1891 under a higher tariff, to 11\nper cent. From 1850 to 1880 under a\nlow tariff the value of American farms\nincreased 102 per cent. From 1880 to\n1890 under a high tariff the value of\nour farming property increased only\n30 per cent. And so comparisons\nmight be made at great length to\nshow that under low tariffs we had\nover three titnes the Increase In our\nnational wealth per capita than we\nhave had during high tariffs. So much\nfor that portion of Mr. Barbour\u2019s and\nMr. Tilson\u2019s erroneous and unfair as\nsertions.\nMR. SHEPARD\u2019S ADMISSION.\nIn this connection we must allude\nto the advertisements being used by\nMr. Andrew Shepard, Republican can\ndidate for Congress in this district in\nwhich he states that in two years Mr.\nTaft has brought the country out or a\nperiod of business depression. Under\nwhose administration did this business\ndepression occur? Is it possible Mr.\nShepard, that the Republican party\nis not after all the solo custodian ar.d\nguarantor of the nation\u2019s prosperity?\nUNFAIR CAMPAIGNING.\nBut to return to Mr. Tilson\u2019a re\nmarks. Not only did our genial con\ngressman erroneouslj' claim too much\nfor the country\u2019s development since\n1SG0; but he pointed out that for only\ntwo short years since that date had\nthe Democratic party had complete\ncontrol of our federal government. Mr.\nTllson, therefore, seems willing that\nhis party should take practically all\nthe credit for the condition of the\ncountry since 1860. Then why\ndoes he saddle off or* the Democratic\nparty- responsibility for the panic of\n1893 which occurred under the Mc\nKinley bill and during a period when\nthe Democratic party were not In com\nplete control of the federal govern\nment? IS TITAT THE FIAR, SQUARE\nCAMPAIGNING WE EXPECT FROM\nGENTLEMEN?\nNO APPLAUSE FOR TAFT.\nThe most significant fact about Mr.\nTilson\u2019s speech was that when he men\ntioned Mr. Taft's name\u2014the first time\nit was mentioned to the audience\u2014\nnot a soul gave it a single bit of ap\nplause. Why-? Because the audience\nknew that Mr. Taft himself, had ad\nmitted that the tariff bill was \u201cnot a\ncomplete compliance with the prom\nise made In the Republican platform.\"\nThey knew that Mr. Tllson, to say the\nleast was Indulging In partisan mis\nrepresentation and exaggeration when\nhe claimed that twenty months of\nTaft had been replete with the enact\nment of measures promised in the Re\npublican platform. It all depends up\non what the voter considers is a fair\ncompliance with these platform pled\nges. Republicans and Taft promised\nto revise the tariff, but, oh! what a re\nvision.\nPAYNE TARIFF BTLL.\nIt Is so bad that 20 Republican con\ngressmen and seven Republican Unit\ned States senators denounced it and\nvoted against it.\nThat several Republican state con\nventions this fall have condemned It.\nThat almost every great independent\nnewspaper and magazine in the\ncountry has severely criticized this\nlaw.\nThat such prominent Republicans\nas Roosevelt, Gifford Pinchot, Gar\nfield, Cummings, Dolllver. Clapp\nBristow, LaFollette, Beveridge, and\nthousands of other prominent and\npatriotic Republicans have severely\ncondemned it.\nThat it has not been successfully\ndefended in a single election that\nhas taken place since it was passed.\nIt was repudiated by the people in\nTHE NEW INTERNATIONAL\nENCYCLOPEDIA SAYS\nCod Liver Oil Is one of\nthe most valuable thera\npeutic agents, that the\nbenefit derived from it in\ndiseases associated with loss\nof flesh cannot be over\nestimated. It Is given in\nTUBERCULOSIS, in\nRICKETS, in CHRONIC\nECZEMA, In many NER\nVOUS DISEASES and in\nGENERAL FEEBLENESS.\nScott\u2019s\nEmulsion\nis the world\u2019s standard preparation of\nCod Liver Oil; it contains no alcohol,\nno drug, or harmful ingredient what\never. It is the original and only\npreparation of Cod Liver Oil rccom\nsWw mended by physicians the\nworld over.\nBe sure to get SCOTT\u2019S,\nknown the world over by the mark\ntrade-mark of quality\u2014The Fisherman.\nALL DRUGGISTS\nThe LATEST\n-IN\nMILLINERY\nVelour\n\u201cDing=A=Ling\u201d Hats\nProbably no hat has ever met with more instant\nor popular favor than this Velour Hat, Black, Brown,\nNavy, Cardinal, Myrtle and Taupe. This particular\nshape is worn by the smartest dressers.\nTRIMMED gg\nUNTRIMMED gg\n$3.98 VELVET turbans at gg\nBeautiful draped Velvet Turbans in all\ncolors. Special Saturday..\n15-19 CHURCH ST. Next Door to Poll\u2019s.\nNew York, Minnesota, Michigan,\nMassachusetts, Pennsylvania and\nMaine, and everywhere it has been\nan issue in a political campaign.\nIt is so bad that it is even en\ndorsed in our Connecticut Republi\ncan state platform this year.\nOTHER REPUBLICAN PROMISES.\nRepublicans also promised the peo\nple a postal savings bank bill, but to\nday the bill passed Is so badly emas\nculated that it bears little or no re\nsemblance to the bill originally con\ntemplated. So far as the railroad bill\nis concerned the President\u2019s own pet\nprovisions were eliminated and other\nbeneficial provisions of the bill ma\nterially modified. Republicans also\npromised us campaign publicity. We\nget It AFTER ELECTION. When the\nhorse is stolen the barn door is\nlocaea.\nWhile we write we have a list of\n12 Important proposals Mr. Taft made\nto the last Republican Congress, five\nof which were acted upon, seven of\nwhich were as good as ignored. Even\nthose enacted into law for the greater\npart appeared in emasculated form.\nYet this is the kind of a Congress Mr.\nTilson and other Republican spell\nbinders insist that Mr. Taft needs.\nTAFT DOESN\u2019T NEED THEM.\nMr. Taft doesn\u2019t say so. He prob\nably is praying hard to be delivered\nfrom such friends, as well he may.\nTAFT DOESN\u2019T NEED MR. TIE\nSON OR HIS KIND HALF AS MUCH\nAS MR. CANNON NEEDS THEM.\nTilson was more a Cannon man in th\u00a3\nlast House than a Taft man. So were\nthe rest of the Connecticut Republi\ncan delegation in Congress. After\nlining up with Cannon against Taft\u2019s\nbest interests and desires during all\nthe last Congress now' they have the\ngall to say \u201cTaft needs us.\"\nTaft certainly does not need any\nbody in Congress who either has the\nignorance or nerve to intimate that\nJudge Baldwin has in this canvass\nabandoned state issues, and is con\nfining himself to national Issues,\nwhich will not concern him as gov\nernor.\nBUSY SIR. TILSON.\nMr. Tilson evidently has been too\nbusy recently to read Judge Bald\nwin\u2019s speeches. If ever a candidate\ndiscussed state isues in a campaign\nit is Judge Baldwin. Is it possible\nthat our Republican friends, unable\nto answer Judge Baldwin\u2019s arguments\non state issues have stooped to mis\nrepresenting him as a man who only\ndiscusses national issues?\nTHEY NOMINATED inM.\nIn introducing Mr. Goodwin, Con\ngressman Tilson said: \u201cTHEY have\nnominated a young man,\u2019\u2019 (meaning\nGoodwin). Who are THEY John?\nDo you allude to the railroad lobby\nists, Roraback, Eaton, King, et al.,\nwho landed the nomination for Mr.\nGoodwin? Or do you allude to the\ngentleman, whom Mr. Goodwin met\ndown at the Dauntless club in Essex\nthe night of the Republican state\nconvention? By the by this young\nman did not say anything Wednesday\nnight about that alleged visit at Es\n1 sex to Cousin J. P. Morgan at or\nabout the time of the Hartford con\nvention? We wonder why? How\never, let Mr. Goodwin speak for him\nself about that and other matters.\nMR. GOODWIN\u2019S SPEECH.\nIn the beginning Mr. Goodwin said\nthat he had studied law at Harvard\ninstead of at Yale under Judge Bald\nwin. That is more Mr. Goodwin's\nthan Judge Baldwin's misfortune.\nIf Mr. Goodwin had studied under\n\u25a0Judge Baldwin he would not have i\naccepted as an example of the ideal\nlawyer the chief counsel of the New\nHaven road. Said Mr. Goodwin in\nspeaking of Edward Robbins Wed\nnesday night: \"The chief counsel of\nthe New Haven road has not a peer\nin Connecticut for legal ability.\" A\nfew days since Mr. Goodwin publicly\ndeclared that J. P. Morgan was one\nof the best and wisest men in the\ntvorld.\nMR. GOODWIN\u2019S IDEALS.\nIt Is significant that the two men\nupon whom Republican Candidate\nGood-win has showered the major\nportion of his praise in this campaign\nare Ed. Robbins, chief counsel for\nthe New Haven road and J. P. Mor\ngan, chief mogul of the road. ARE\nTHESE THE MEN WHO ARE TO\nHAVE MR. GOODWIN\u2019S CONFI\nDENCE, IF HE IS ELECTED GOV\nERNOR? Why not? Will they not\nprove vrorthy successors in this confi\ndential role to the railroad lobbyists,\nRoraback, Eaton, King, et al., who\nwere Mr. Goodwin's confidence men\nin the getting of the Republican nom\nination for governor?\nABOUT CORRUPTION.\nAnd this brings us to what Mr.\nGoodwin said or did not say about\npolitical corruption In this state this\nyear. Mr. Goodwin neither affirmed\nnor denied that he had visited J. P.\nMorgan at Essex on or about the date\nof the Republican Hartford conven\ntion. He neither affirmed nor denied\nMr. Lake\u2019s intimation that while Mr.\nMorgan was not \u201cPERSONALLY\u201d\npresent at Hartford during the pro\nceedings of the Republican conven\ntion that he -was there by agent or\nProtoben\nFIGS\nare just the\nplain garden variety of\nnatural Turkish Figs\u2014\npacked with extra care\nso as not to split the\nhe sk n but keep the fruit whole and\nntact as it comes from the orchard.\nNo other Fig grown anywhere, sold at\niany price, packed either in parchment\npaper, fancy box or glass jar, tver\nequalled them for natural, genuine, un\nprocessed Fig goodness.\nAll Figs are at their best when the new\ncrop has just arrived\u2014that\u2019s now.\nBy the pound, 22 cts.\nBox of 3 lbs. 68 cts.\nSiuX&tfaMf&iti\n-38/ JH'o&.Si?\nproxy. He neither affirmed nor de\nnied the truth or falsity of the cases\nof corruption that Mr. Fox has put\nup to Prosecuting Attorney Hugh Al\ncorn of Hartford. He neither affirm\ned nor denied that he had spent a\nlarge sum of money In order to get\nthe Republican gubernatorial nomi\nnation at Hartford, although .fudge\nBaldwin has repeatedly aBked him\nhow much this nomination cost him.\nMr. Goodwin's answer to this fair\nquestion Is a silent confession of\nguilt. In lieu of a better reply he\nasks his Interrogators to produce their\nevidence of corruption, forgetting\nthat they have repeatedly done so.\nCAMPAIGN PUBRICITY.\nDoes Mr. Goodwin favor campaign\npublicity before election? If so,\nwhy doesn\u2019t he come forward and\ntell the people exactly what his nom\nination for governor cost, who con\ntributed, and who spent the money\n(Continued on Fifth Page.)\nSupplies for\nBRASS CRAFTERS\nCHE most fascinating fad tha out\namateur craftsmen have take up\nfor some time is the pierce ot\nformed brass work. To one who at\nsome manual skill this work opens o\nalmost unlimited opportunities for pro\nducing very artistic results.\nOur business in the supplies needed for\nthis work has grown to such an extent\nthat we have put a competent man in\ncharge and are carrying a stock that\ncovers the whole line of tools and\nmaterials.\nTHE LINE INCLUDES\nPunches, Pliers, Mallets; Sheet Brass,\nCopper and German Silver; Gold, Silver,\nGreen and Red Fringe; Chain, Metal\nPolish, Lacquer; Designs on Paper 01\nBrass, and also a 1 arge line of Bras\nCovered Novelties.\nThe John E. Bassett CgL Co.\nflTm OLD. HABDe-.'WABB STOBE\n75*-75\u00bb Chapel 31* State S*\nThe longer you use a\nBRASS\nBED\nthe better satlstled you will be.\nThey are so sanitary\u2014so easy to\nkeep clean\u2014so attractive In ap\npearance that you will wonder\nwhy you didn\u2019t purchase one\nsooner. Then, too, our prices are\nright.\n918.00 to 900.00.\nTHE P. J. KELLY\nFURNITURE CO.\n817-823 GRAND AVE.,\n86-38 CllrTtCTI ST.\nOpen Monday and Saturday\nEvenings.\nI\n\ni\nThe Yale National Bank\nCor. State Chapel Sts.\nF RE AND BURGLARS\ndo not give warning. P/ovida against\nthsse by ren ing a Sals De:o.U Box in\ncur fire and burg ar-prool vaults\nSate Deposit Boxes lor the fate keeping ol valuable\n$5.00 a vear","height":"25660","width":"19812"}}
